ing a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Oscar","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Old Irish name , which is borne in the Fenian sagas by a grandson of  Finn mac Cumhaill  (  Finn MacCool ). It was resuscitated by the antiquarian poet  James Macpherson  (  1736–96 ), author of the Ossian poems. It is now also a characteristically Scandinavian name; it was introduced to Sweden because  Napoleon , an admirer of the works of  Macpherson , imposed the name on his godson Oscar Bernadotte, who became  King Oscar I  of Sweden in  1844  (  see also  Malvina  ). In more recent times it has been associated particularly with the Irish writer and wit  Oscar Wilde  (  1854–1900 ), and with the annual awards for achievement in the film industry made by the American Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences. Oscar is one of a number of Celtic names that have recently come into general use and have become increasingly popular since the 1990s."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Oscar de Marieux was born in 1052, in Marieux, Somme, Hauts-de-France, France, his father, Gregoire de Marieux, was 27 and his mother, Jossine de Raincheval, was 20. He married Jehanne de Beauquesne in 1079, in Beauquesne, Somme, Hauts-de-France, France. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 4 daughters. He died in 1103, at the age of 51."},"et":{"1052–1103":"1052–1103","1055–1109":"1055–1109","1061–1109":"1061–1109","1080–1129":"1080–1129","1081–1135":"1081–1135","1082–1127":"1082–1127","1084–1137":"1084–1137","1092–1143":"1092–1143","1025–1089":"1025–1089","1032–1089":"1032–1089","1080":"1080","1143":"1143","1055":"1055","1032":"1032","1052":"1052","1084":"1084","1061":"1061","1082":"1082","1081":"1081","1092":"1092","1129":"1129","1127":"1127","1049":"1049","1137":"1137","1103":"1103","1025":"1025","1135":"1135","1079":"1079"